window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "five-suns",
    title: "The Five Suns",
    subtitle: "Four worlds destroyed, and the fifth turning above us by sacrifice",
    civilization: "aztec",
    themes: ["Cosmic cycles", "Creation", "Destruction", "Sacrifice"],
    content: [
        "The world we live in, the priests of Tenochtitlan taught, is the fifth world. There were four others before this one. Each was lit by a different sun. Each ended in the way it had been built to end. The fifth, ours, has not ended yet, but it will, in the way it was built to end, and the priests counted the days because the priests believed that knowing the day of one's own ending was a small kindness one could do for one's children.",
        "The first sun was the Sun of Earth. The god Tezcatlipoca, the smoking mirror, the trickster — he with the obsidian foot — became the first sun and lit the world for many ages. The world he lit was a world of giants. The giants were strong and slow. They ate acorns. They lived patiently. But Tezcatlipoca and his rival, Quetzalcoatl, the feathered serpent, quarreled — they had been quarreling since before there were anything to quarrel about — and Quetzalcoatl struck Tezcatlipoca out of the sky. The first sun fell. The light went out. In the darkness, jaguars came up out of the earth and ate the giants, every one of them. The first world ended in teeth.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The second sun was the Sun of Wind. Quetzalcoatl, having struck down his brother, took his place in the sky. The world he lit was a world of ordinary men, the first ordinary men. They lived. They built small huts. They ate seeds. They were not yet what they would become. But Tezcatlipoca was not finished, and from his place in the dark he raised a great wind — a wind that blew without stopping for an age — and the wind tore the second world apart. The huts were lifted into the air. The men were lifted into the air. Most of them were thrown into the trees, and there they hung, and slowly, over generations, they hooked their fingers into the branches and grew brown fur and chittering voices, and they became, the priests said, the monkeys you can still see in the high jungle. The second world ended in air.",
        "The third sun was the Sun of Rain. The god Tlaloc, lord of storms, became the sun. He had not wanted to be the sun. He had a wife who had been taken from him by Tezcatlipoca, and he was in mourning. He sat in the sky weeping, and his weeping fell as a slow rain, and the world below was lit only dimly, because his head was bent. But after a time the weeping stopped, and Tlaloc, who had grown angry, hurled fire from the sky instead of water. Fire from the sky for a season. The mountains opened up and answered the fire with fire. The rivers boiled away. The crops burned. The third world ended in flame, and the people who survived became, the priests said, the small dogs you see at every house, the long-snouted, half-trusted ones, who remember dimly what it was to be men in the third sun.",
        "The fourth sun was the Sun of Water. The goddess Chalchiuhtlicue, lady of the rivers, lady of the jade skirt, took up the office. She was beloved. The world she lit was a world of music, and the people of her world made flutes and sang at every meal and grew tall in a quiet rain. But Tezcatlipoca, the same restless god, said to her one day, \"You smile too much. You are not really kind. You only pretend.\" The accusation was not true, but the goddess heard it, and the saying of it broke her, and she wept blood for fifty-two years, and the weeping became a flood that covered the world, and every house was carried away, and every person was carried away. The people who survived became, the priests said, the silver fish you can still see in the deep lakes, who remember in their small flickering minds the music they once made.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "After the fourth world ended, the gods met in the dark. They sat around a small fire on a flat rock at a place called Teotihuacan — a place that would later become a great city, but in those days was only a flat rock under a black sky — and they argued.",
        "\"Someone must be the next sun,\" they said. \"Someone must throw himself into the fire. Whoever throws himself into the fire will become the new sun. There must be a sun. The world below must have light again, or there will be no fifth age.\"",
        "There were two volunteers.",
        "The first was a god named Tecciztecatl. He was vain. He was beautiful. He wore green-feather garments and gold ornaments and he had been waiting all his eternity for a moment of glory. He stepped forward at once.",
        "The second was a god named Nanahuatzin. He was small. He was sick. His body was covered in sores from a long affliction. He had been a humble god — a god of the sick and the broken — and he had not expected to be considered. But he stepped forward also. He had nothing else to give. He had only himself, and his self was a sick small body, and he was willing to give it.",
        "The fire was built up. The fire was made enormous. The flames stood tall as a mountain. The two gods stood at the edge.",
        "Tecciztecatl, the beautiful one, was given the first turn. He prepared himself. He took a few steps toward the fire. The heat hit him. He stopped. He took a few more steps. The heat hit him harder. He stopped again. He went back to the starting place. He tried again. The same thing happened. Four times he tried. Four times he stopped. He could not bring himself to do it. He stood at the starting place looking at the fire.",
        "Nanahuatzin, the small sick one, did not stop. He closed his eyes. He took a single breath. He ran. He ran straight into the fire. The flames closed over him. He was gone.",
        "The other gods, ashamed for Tecciztecatl, called out, \"Now you. Now you must go.\" Tecciztecatl, his pride finally cornered, ran, also, into the fire. But he was second. He had hesitated. He went in second.",
        "The fire burned higher.",
        "After a time, in the east, a small light appeared on the horizon. It grew. It rose. It was the new sun. It was Nanahuatzin — sick, small, brave Nanahuatzin — and his face shone, the face he had been ashamed of in his life, shone now over the dark world with a brightness no eye could rest on, and the world below woke up at the touch of him.",
        "Then, behind him, in the east also, a second light rose. It was Tecciztecatl, the beautiful one, who had hesitated and gone in second. He shone too. He shone almost as brightly. The gods, looking up, said, \"This is wrong. There cannot be two suns of equal brightness in the same sky. The one who deserved it must be brighter.\" One of the gods picked up a rabbit from beside the fire and hurled it at Tecciztecatl's face. The rabbit struck him, and his face dimmed, and the small dark mark of the rabbit stayed on him, and he became the moon, and you can still see the rabbit on the face of the moon to this night, sitting in his patient outline, and that is why he is dimmer.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "But the new sun, Nanahuatzin, did not move.",
        "He sat in the east. He shone. He did not begin his journey across the sky.",
        "The gods called up to him. \"Begin your travel. Go.\" He answered, in a voice that came down from the fire of him, \"I will not move until you have given what I gave. I burned myself for you. You also must burn for me. Otherwise I will not move, and the world below will be lit on one side only, and the other side will be dark forever.\"",
        "The gods understood. They considered. Then, one by one, they offered themselves at the same fire. Each god threw himself in. The wind-god Ehecatl alone survived, to walk across the world afterward and tell the story. The other gods burned. And only when all of them had burned did the new sun begin, slowly, to roll along the rim of the sky, and the day began, and the night followed.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The sun above us was bought by gods who threw themselves into a fire. The contract is renewed by us, in our small ways, every day. Whoever lives without paying anything into the fire is, at best, a guest." },
        "And from that day forward, the priests of the fifth world said, the sun must be paid. Not in the great way that the gods paid — not by self-immolation — but in offerings, in care, in attention. The priests offered drops of their own blood from their pierced earlobes at sunrise. The kings did the same. The people, in their houses, paused at noon. And in this way the fifth sun has continued to roll, and it will continue to roll, until the day that has been counted out comes — but that day, the priests said, is not yet."
    ]
},

{
    id: "quetzalcoatl",
    title: "Quetzalcoatl and the Bones of the Underworld",
    subtitle: "How the feathered serpent stole the bones of the dead to make us",
    civilization: "aztec",
    themes: ["Creation", "Trickery", "Self-sacrifice", "Humanity"],
    content: [
        "After the fourth world had ended in flood, the new sun rose in the sky and lit a world that had no people in it. The fish that had been people swam in the lakes. The monkeys that had been people swung in the trees. The dogs that had been people slept by the cold hearths of houses that had no families. But there were no men. The fifth sun was lighting an empty stage.",
        "The gods, around the fire at Teotihuacan, looked at each other. \"There must be people,\" they said. \"The sun is paid. The sun is rolling. But the sun rolls for nothing if there is no one to receive its light, no one to make corn from its warmth, no one to lift a hand at sunrise and lower it at sunset and call the day a day. We need people. We must make people again.\"",
        "But the bones of the previous people — the bones of the giants, the bones of the men of the wind, the bones of the men of the rain, the bones of the men of the water — had all gone down, after each ending, to the lowest country. They were stored there. They were stored in the boneyard of Mictlan, the land of the dead, ruled by Mictlantecuhtli, the lord of the dead.",
        "Mictlantecuhtli was a difficult god. He was not cruel exactly. He was bureaucratic. He kept what he had been given to keep. He had been keeping bones for a long time. He had no intention of releasing any.",
        "Quetzalcoatl, the feathered serpent — beautiful god, gentle god, the god of wind and learning and cool morning — said quietly, \"I'll go.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He went down. He took his twin Xolotl with him for company; Xolotl was a dog-headed god, the god of twins and of misshapen things, and he had been Quetzalcoatl's shadow since the beginning. The two of them descended through nine layers of the lower country. Each layer was an obstacle. They crossed a river of obsidian knives. They crossed a place where the wind blew so hard it stripped the feathers off Quetzalcoatl's body and the dog-fur off Xolotl. They walked between two clashing mountains that almost crushed them. They came at last to the throne of Mictlantecuhtli.",
        "The lord of the dead was a tall figure. He was wearing a paper crown and a necklace of small skulls. He had a face that looked like a skull also, but was a face. He looked at the two travelers with mild curiosity.",
        "\"What do you want,\" he said.",
        "\"I would like the bones,\" said Quetzalcoatl. \"The precious bones. Of the people of the previous worlds. We are making people again, in the upper country, and we need the material.\"",
        "Mictlantecuhtli considered. He had not expected this request. He had no rule, on the books, for releasing bones. He decided to be playful.",
        "\"I'll give them to you,\" he said, \"if you can perform a small task for me. Take this conch shell. It has no holes in it. Carry it four times around my throne, blowing it as a trumpet. Then you may have the bones.\"",
        "He handed Quetzalcoatl a conch shell. The shell was solid. There was no mouthpiece. There was no way to blow it.",
        "Quetzalcoatl took the shell. He went a little way off. He thought. Then he called, very softly, to the worms — for he was a god of patient detail, and worms answered to him as well as the wind did — and the worms came. The worms drilled small spiral holes through the shell. He called next to the bees, who came, and the bees crawled into the new holes and buzzed.",
        "He went back to the throne. He blew. The shell, full of bees, sang.",
        "He carried it around the throne four times, blowing.",
        "Mictlantecuhtli's eyes narrowed. He had not expected this. \"Very well,\" he said. \"You may take the bones. But — \" and his eyes narrowed further \" — they must not be taken in pieces. You must take the whole load. Whole. In one trip. Out the way you came. Do you understand?\"",
        "\"I understand,\" said Quetzalcoatl.",
        "He went to the boneyard. He gathered the bones — a great heap, men's and women's, leg and skull and rib — into a single bundle. He hoisted them onto his back. He turned to leave.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Mictlantecuhtli, behind him, made a small gesture. He said, conversationally, to a quail-bird that lived in his throne-room: \"Frighten him.\"",
        "The quail flew up suddenly into Quetzalcoatl's face. He flinched. He stumbled. He fell forward. The bones came off his back. They scattered on the floor of the lower country. They broke. Some snapped clean in half. Some chipped. Some shattered into many pieces.",
        "Quetzalcoatl, on his hands and knees, gathered them as best he could. He was not allowed, by the agreement, to leave any behind. He put the broken pieces back into his bundle. He stood up. He carried the broken bundle out.",
        "Mictlantecuhtli watched him go without saying anything. The quail-bird hopped contentedly on the floor.",
        "Quetzalcoatl came up through the nine layers. He came at last back to the upper country. He laid the broken bones at the feet of the goddess Cihuacoatl, the snake-woman, who was the master craftsman of the gods. She ground the bones into a fine meal. She mixed the meal with corn-flour. She mixed it, also — and this was the important part — with blood that Quetzalcoatl drew from his own body. He cut his earlobe. He cut his tongue. He let his blood drip into the meal. The other gods, ashamed, came forward and added their blood also.",
        "Cihuacoatl shaped the meal. She shaped it into small figures — the first men, the first women — and she breathed on them, and they sat up.",
        "They sat up imperfect. Because the bones had been broken, none of the figures was the same height. Some were tall. Some were short. Some were broad. Some were slender. Some had stronger left sides than right sides. None of them was, in the eyes of Mictlantecuhtli's strict bureaucracy, a complete restoration. We are all, the priests said, to this day, a little broken. We are all a little stumbled-on by a quail.",
        "But we are also, the priests said — and this was the better half of the teaching — kneaded with the blood of a god. The god went down into the country of the dead and took us out at his own risk. The god cut his own earlobe and his own tongue to make us. We are unfinished, but we are paid for.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Whoever sits up in the morning sits up partly because a god, very long ago, was startled by a bird and did not give up. The startle is in us. So is the not giving up." },
        "Quetzalcoatl, having made the people, walked among them for a long time afterward. He taught them how to plant the corn, how to weave, how to read the stars, how to keep a calendar. He was their gentle god. When at last he had to leave — for he was driven out at last, in another story, by his old brother Tezcatlipoca, who had never stopped quarreling with him — he sailed east on a raft of serpents into the sea, and the people on the shore wept, and he turned at the horizon and said he would come back. The day he chose to come back, he said, would be a day in a particular year, in a particular cycle, the date marked clearly in the priests' books. And the priests, ever after, watched for that day. They had a sign for it on the wall of every temple. They were watching for it the year the strangers from across the sea — pale-skinned, helmeted — came up out of the eastern water, and the priests, looking up, were not sure, at first, what they were seeing — but that, also, is another story."
    ]
}
);


window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "gilgamesh",
    title: "Gilgamesh and the Quest for Immortality",
    subtitle: "The first hero who could not bear that his friend had died",
    civilization: "mesopotamian",
    themes: ["Friendship", "Mortality", "Quest", "Acceptance"],
    content: [
        "Gilgamesh was two-thirds god and one-third man — the records are precise about the ratio — and he was the king of the great walled city of Uruk in the time when cities were a new kind of thing. He had built the wall of Uruk himself: thick brick, tall, the courses still visible after four thousand years. He was tall, beautiful, terrible. He was also bored, and a bored king is a heavy king, and the people of Uruk had begun to murmur. He took the brides on their wedding nights. He worked the young men ragged at games. The gods heard the complaints, and the gods made him a counterweight.",
        "His name was Enkidu. He had been made out of clay, in the wilderness, by the goddess Aruru — made wild on purpose, made the equal of Gilgamesh on purpose, made hairy and strong and able to run with the gazelles he ran with. He had been brought into the city by a temple-woman, who tamed him in the only way the stories had a vocabulary for, and he had walked into the great square of Uruk just as Gilgamesh was coming down the steps to take a bride.",
        "They fought at the threshold. They fought through the door. They fought across the floor of the wedding-hall. They were exactly matched. After hours of it they pulled apart, panting, equally bruised, and they began — slowly, the way two men who have measured each other in the only honest measurement begin — to laugh. They embraced. The wedding was forgotten. The bride went home. The king and the wild man walked out of the hall with their arms across each other's shoulders, and from that day they were inseparable.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They went on adventures. They killed the great monster Humbaba in the cedar forest of the west. They killed the Bull of Heaven that the goddess Ishtar had sent against them after Gilgamesh insulted her. They were the kind of friends who could spend a week in silence in the saddle and still know what the other was thinking.",
        "But the gods had been counting. Two great heroes had killed two great gifts of the gods — Humbaba had been Enlil's, the Bull had been Ishtar's — and someone had to pay. The council of gods met. They decided. Gilgamesh was two-thirds divine; they could not, by the rules of the upper country, simply kill him. Enkidu, who was clay, was within their reach.",
        "Enkidu fell sick.",
        "He fell sick in his bed in the palace at Uruk. He grew weaker by the day. The fever came and went. He spoke, between fevers, of dreams he was having — of a dark country with dust on the floor and birds eating the dust because there was nothing else, of crowned kings sitting in the dust without crowns, of priests sitting without their robes — the underworld, he was saying, the underworld, and he was trying to describe it for his friend so that his friend would not be surprised by it later.",
        "He died on the twelfth day. Gilgamesh held his hand throughout. When the hand went cold he did not let go. He sat there for a long time. He did not weep. He did not know how, yet. He thought, perhaps, that this was a trick — that the wild man would sit up, laughing, in a moment, and demand wine.",
        "It was when a fly settled on Enkidu's open eye and Enkidu did not blink that Gilgamesh understood, and the cry that came out of him went up over the wall of Uruk and was heard, the records say, in a country two days' ride away.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He could not stay in the city. He could not bear his bed. He took off his royal clothes. He put on the rough skin of a lion he had killed long ago. He walked out of Uruk by the western gate. He went to find a man named Utnapishtim — the only mortal who had ever been granted immortality by the gods, the man who had built the great boat in the days of the long flood and had survived, and who lived now beyond the world, on a far shore. Gilgamesh would ask him how he had done it. Gilgamesh would not die.",
        "He walked across the world. He went past the foothills, past the high mountains where the lions still hunted at the headwaters of every river, past the long pass guarded by the scorpion-men who knew him by name and let him through because they pitied him, into the darkness under the mountain of Mashu where the sun travels at night, twelve double-hours of darkness in which he could see nothing — and at the twelfth hour he came out into a garden of jeweled trees, every leaf carnelian, every fruit lapis, and a tavern-keeper named Siduri sat at the edge of the world brewing beer for the gods who passed by.",
        "Siduri looked at him. She was a hard woman with kind eyes. She said, \"Gilgamesh. Where are you going?\"",
        "\"I am looking for Utnapishtim. I cannot die.\"",
        "She said, gently, \"Listen to me, Gilgamesh. The life you are looking for, you will not find. When the gods made man they gave death its due and kept life for themselves. Wash your head. Put on clean clothes. Eat your fill. Make your wife happy. Let your children sit on your knee. This is the lot of man.\"",
        "He stared at her. He had heard, all his life, the kind of advice she was offering. He shook his head. He kept walking.",
        "She sighed. She told him where to find the boatman, Urshanabi, who could take him across the waters of death.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He found Utnapishtim at last. The old man was sitting on a porch at the far edge of the world. He looked, more or less, like an ordinary old man. He listened to the king's story patiently. He asked one question.",
        "\"Can you stay awake,\" he said, \"for six days and seven nights?\"",
        "Gilgamesh laughed. Of course he could. He was Gilgamesh.",
        "He sat down on the porch. He fell asleep within an hour. He slept for six days and seven nights. Utnapishtim, every morning, baked a small loaf of bread and laid it beside him. By the seventh morning the first loaf was hard as a brick, the second was crusted, the third was leaning, the fourth was stale, the fifth was almost-fresh, the sixth was warm, and the seventh was just baked. When Gilgamesh woke he saw the row of loaves and understood, without being told, that he had failed the smallest test of immortality. He could not even outwait sleep. How was he going to outwait death?",
        "He wept then, properly, for the first time. He wept for Enkidu. He wept for himself. He wept for the wall of Uruk that he would have to leave behind. Utnapishtim watched him weep without moving. After a while the old man said, \"Stand up. Wash. Go home. There is one thing I will give you — a plant, at the bottom of a deep pool, that grows here. It is called Old Man Becomes Young Again. It will not make you immortal. But it will let you live a long time, and start over once. Take it.\"",
        "Gilgamesh dove. He came up with the plant, thorned, dripping. He set out for home. On the way back, by a sweet pool where he had stopped to bathe, a snake came out of the reeds and ate the plant while he washed, and slid back into the reeds shedding its old skin behind it as a coin. Gilgamesh sat in the water and could not even be angry. He had been outwitted by a snake. He had been outwitted by a sleep. He had been outwitted by the simplest mechanisms of the world.",
        "He went home. He came to the wall of Uruk at dusk. He stood outside it. He looked up at it. He had built it. The bricks were still good. The courses were straight. The city behind it was full of his people, and the people had children, and the children would have children, and the wall would stand a long time.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The immortality you can have is not the one you went looking for. It is the wall you laid the bricks of, the friend you held the hand of, the long even courses of the work you actually did." },
        "He went in through the gate. He took off the lion-skin. He put on his royal cloth. He sat on his throne again. He ruled, by all accounts, more gently than before. When he died — for he did die, eventually, and the records are careful to record it — the people of Uruk wept for him for many days, and they buried him under the floor of the river by diverting the river's flow and laying him in the bed of it and then letting the river back, so that no enemy could ever disturb him, and the river runs over him still."
    ]
},

{
    id: "inanna",
    title: "Inanna's Descent to the Underworld",
    subtitle: "Seven gates, seven garments, and a sister who was waiting",
    civilization: "mesopotamian",
    themes: ["Sister", "Stripping", "Death", "Substitution"],
    content: [
        "Inanna was the queen of heaven and the queen of earth. She ruled love and war and the morning star and the evening star. She had cities. She had lovers. She had a husband, the shepherd-god Dumuzi, who was beautiful and rather lazy and inclined to lounge in the spring grass while she ran the world. She had a sister.",
        "Her sister's name was Ereshkigal, and Ereshkigal lived in the underworld. They had not seen each other in a long time. Ereshkigal had been queen of the lower country since before there were memories of when she had not been; she had been there when the first soul descended, and she had stayed, and she had grown bitter in the way the keeper of any thankless office grows bitter, and her hall was dark, and her throne was black, and she sat on the throne with her chin in her hand most of the time, and the dust gathered.",
        "Inanna heard, one day, that her sister's husband had died. The funeral was being held in the lower country. Inanna decided — for reasons that even her own attendants did not fully understand, perhaps grief, perhaps an instinct that the lower country needed her, perhaps simple ambition to rule both kingdoms — that she would go down for the funeral.",
        "She dressed for it. She put on the seven garments of her power. The crown of the steppe, the small lapis beads at her throat, the double strand of beads on her breast, the breastplate \"Come, man, come,\" the gold ring on her wrist, the lapis measuring rod and line in her hand, the royal robe of office. She was the queen of the upper world descending to the lower world; she meant to look it.",
        "Before she left she went to her vizier Ninshubur, who was a faithful woman, and she said, \"If I have not returned in three days, raise the alarm. Go to the high gods. Tell them what I have done. Beg them to bring me back.\" Ninshubur swore she would. Inanna went down.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She came to the great gate of the underworld. The gatekeeper, an old man named Neti, looked at her. He sent word in to Ereshkigal. Ereshkigal, on her dark throne, raised her head. She had not been expecting her sister. She thought, slowly: ah. She thought: of course. She gave Neti instructions.",
        "\"Open the gate to her,\" she said, \"but make her enter as everyone enters — naked and bowed, as the dead enter, with nothing of the upper country left on her. There are seven gates. At each gate, take from her one piece of her finery. By the seventh gate she will be naked. She will be a thing the way every thing here is a thing. Then bring her in.\"",
        "Neti went out. He told Inanna the rules. She did not protest. She walked through the first gate. The crown of the steppe was lifted from her head. She did not stop. She walked through the second. The lapis beads at her throat were taken. The third: the small beads of her breast. The fourth: the breastplate. The fifth: the gold ring at her wrist. The sixth: the lapis rod and the measuring line. The seventh: the royal robe.",
        "She walked into Ereshkigal's hall naked.",
        "Ereshkigal looked at her sister for a long moment. She looked at the small mortal-looking shape in front of her — for stripped of her ornaments, even Inanna looked a little mortal — and Ereshkigal made a small noise that was not quite a laugh, and the seven judges of the underworld, who sat in a half-ring around her, fixed Inanna with their dead eyes, and they pronounced their verdict: guilty. Of what? Of presumption. Of crossing a border she had no business crossing.",
        "Ereshkigal struck her sister. She turned her into a piece of meat. She hung the meat on a hook on the wall of her hall.",
        "And there Inanna stayed, three days and three nights.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Up above, Ninshubur counted. Three days passed. Inanna did not return. The vizier did exactly as she had been told. She put on the rough cloth of mourning. She went to the high gods.",
        "She went first to Enlil, king of the gods of the upper country. He listened. He shook his head. \"Inanna chose to go,\" he said. \"What is the underworld must remain in the underworld. We do not bring back the dead.\"",
        "She went to Nanna, the moon-god, Inanna's father. He said the same thing. He wept, but he said the same thing.",
        "She went to Enki, god of fresh water and of wisdom and of old kindness. Enki listened. Enki — who had always loved Inanna a little, and who knew the underworld in a way the others did not — said, \"Wait. Let me think.\"",
        "He scraped the dirt from under his fingernails. He kneaded the dirt into two small figures. He breathed on them. They came alive — small, sexless, made of dirt and wisdom. Their names were Galatur and Kurgarra. They were not gods. They were not mortals. They could pass through the gates of the underworld without paying the toll, because they had nothing for the gates to take.",
        "He gave them the water of life and the food of life. He sent them down. He told them what to do.",
        "They came to Ereshkigal's hall. Ereshkigal was lying on her side on the throne, moaning. She was — for reasons no one entirely understood, perhaps because the killing of her sister had broken something in her, perhaps because her own dead husband's funeral had finally caught up with her — in the long throes of a grief she had been postponing for centuries. She moaned, \"Oh, my belly.\" The two small dirt-creatures said, \"Oh, your belly.\" She moaned, \"Oh, my back.\" They said, \"Oh, your back.\" She had not been pitied in three thousand years. The pity, even from such small messengers, undid her.",
        "She raised her head. She said, \"Ask anything. Anything I have.\"",
        "They said, \"The piece of meat on the hook on the wall. Give us that.\"",
        "She blinked. \"That?\" she said. \"That is nothing.\" But she gave it.",
        "They took it down. They sprinkled it with the food of life. They sprinkled it with the water of life. The piece of meat became, slowly, Inanna again. The seven garments came back. She rose to her feet.",
        "Ereshkigal, when she understood what had happened, was furious for a moment, then resigned. \"You may go,\" she said. \"But the law is the law. No one leaves the underworld without leaving someone in their place. Pick a substitute. Send them down.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Inanna went up. The demons of the underworld followed her at a small distance, watching, waiting to see who she would name.",
        "She came up into the city of Uruk. Ninshubur was there, waiting, in mourning cloth, weeping. The demons looked at Ninshubur with interest. Inanna shook her head. Not her. She had been faithful.",
        "She went to the temple. Her two sons were there, also in mourning cloth, weeping. Not them. They had loved her.",
        "She came at last to the courtyard of her own house. There she found her husband, Dumuzi. Dumuzi was sitting on his fine throne in his fine clothes. He was eating. He was laughing. He had not put on mourning at all. He had taken her absence as a kind of holiday. He looked, all in all, as if he had spent the three days enjoying himself.",
        "Inanna's face — the face of a woman just back from a hook on a wall — went very still.",
        "\"Him,\" she said, and pointed. \"Take him.\"",
        "The demons closed in.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There is a kind of grief that, when not paid by those who should have paid it, is collected later, by other parties, with interest. The husband who would not mourn was sent down to learn what mourning meant." },
        "Dumuzi was dragged down. He spent half of every year afterwards in the underworld, and his sister Geshtinanna, who loved him, took the other half in his place — and so the country had its dry season and its wet season, the green and the parched, in turn, by the rotation of those two siblings going down and coming up, paying off in installments the bill that Inanna had run up at her sister's gate."
    ]
}
);


window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "children-of-lir",
    title: "The Children of Lir",
    subtitle: "Nine hundred years as swans on the cold lakes of Ireland",
    civilization: "celtic",
    themes: ["Stepmother", "Curses", "Time", "Forgiveness"],
    content: [
        "Lir was a sea-king of the Tuatha Dé Danann, the old gods of Ireland, and he had four children by his first wife — a daughter named Fionnuala, who was the eldest, and three sons, Aodh and the twins Fiachra and Conn. Their mother died bringing the twins into the world, and Lir was unmade by it for a long time, walking the cliffs of his country alone in the high winds.",
        "After some years he married again, for the children's sake more than his own. Aoife was his second wife, the sister of his first. He had thought a sister would love them as a mother would. She did, for a year. The children were beautiful — brown-eyed, fair-haired, with a kind of singing in them that even strangers noticed. Fionnuala took her brothers' braids out and rebraided them every morning. The brothers fought sometimes, but never for long, and they slept in a single bed with the twins on either end and Aodh in the middle and Fionnuala on the floor at the foot like a watching cat. The whole household revolved around them.",
        "Aoife saw it. She watched her husband's face when the children entered a room. She watched the servants' faces. She felt herself grow smaller in the rooms they were in. The watching grew to envy. The envy grew, by slow patient inches, to a hatred that surprised her with its quality, since she did love them, in her way, and was therefore the kind of person who must hide a hatred even from herself.",
        "She told them one morning that she would take them to visit their grandfather. They climbed gladly into the chariot beside her. They sang as they drove. They did not see the look she had begun to wear.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "She stopped the chariot at Lake Derravaragh. She told them to bathe. They were tired and hot from the road, and they ran down to the water laughing, and they dropped their tunics on the sand, and they waded in. Aoife stood on the shore. She held a thin white druidic wand she had not let them see her packing.",
        "She raised the wand. She spoke a word that broke her own voice as she said it.",
        "The four children — Fionnuala thirteen years old, Aodh nine, the twins seven — became four white swans in the water. The transformation came on them with no pain, only the strange unaccountable cool of feathers where there had been skin, and they looked at each other in that bewildered moment of new bodies, and Fionnuala — who was Fionnuala still, her mind still her mind — said in a voice that was no longer her voice but theirs, \"What have you done to us?\"",
        "Aoife trembled. She had not, perhaps, fully meant it. But the working was done.",
        "\"Three hundred years on this lake,\" she said, her voice splintering. \"Three hundred years on the Sea of Moyle, between Ireland and Scotland. Three hundred years on Erris, in the western wild. Nine hundred years in all. The spell can only be broken when a holy man's bell sounds for the first time over Ireland — and that, in the days I am banishing you to, is a sound that will not be heard for many centuries. You will keep your minds. You will keep your voices when you sing. That is the only mercy I can leave you. I cannot take it back.\"",
        "She turned the chariot. She drove on alone to the grandfather's house. The grandfather, when she arrived, asked where the children were. She lied. She said they had been left at home. He went out walking by Lake Derravaragh that very afternoon, and he saw four white swans on the water, and one of them began to sing in his eldest grandchild's voice, and he understood at once.",
        "He went home in white fury. He turned Aoife into a demon of the air with his own druid's stick, and the air swept her up and she was scattered to the winds, and that was the last of her, and there was no satisfaction in it.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The four swans stayed on Lake Derravaragh for three hundred years. The water was sweet. The reeds were tall. People came to the shore to listen to them sing — for they sang every evening, and the songs they sang were the old songs of the Tuatha, and the songs themselves were a kind of slow time-keeping, a way to live a swan's life and remain, inside, a child's mind. Lir came too, often, with his cloak over his head, and he sat on the bank and wept, and Fionnuala swam over and bent her long white neck and laid her head against his cheek, and the two of them stayed like that, motionless, until the dusk.",
        "After three hundred years they had to fly to the Sea of Moyle, between Ireland and Scotland. The sea there was cold. The cold was in their bones. They were thrown apart by storms; they hunted each other in the waves for hours, calling, before they were sure they had not lost a brother. Fiachra one winter had ice frozen to his beak and could not eat for days, and the others tucked him under their wings to thaw him, and he survived because they shared their warmth.",
        "After three more centuries they flew to the western wild of Erris, where the cliffs were sheer and the sea broke white at the rocks. They had been swans now for six hundred years. Their parents were dust. Their friends were dust. Their kingdom was a small ring of stones overgrown by moss. The world had become Christian. A new kind of stone building stood on hilltops where the old halls had been. They had heard, from the wind, the rumor of a new bell — a small, sweet, unfamiliar sound, made of bronze, struck by a man in a robe.",
        "They flew, at the end of the third three hundred years, back to the lake of their childhood. They were old now, even as swans. They saw, by the lake, a small wooden chapel, and outside the chapel a saint named Mochaomhog was ringing a small bronze bell to call the people to prayer.",
        "The four swans alighted on the lake. The bell rang. The bell rang again.",
        "And the white feathers on each of them rose, and fell, and rose, and fell, and slipped — not all at once, not gently, but with the long ache of nine hundred years compressed into a single minute — and four ancient figures stood in the shallows, their hair white as the feathers had been, their bodies thin as winter reeds, eyes the same brown eyes they had taken to the bath all those centuries ago.",
        { style: "quote", text: "A curse of nine hundred years is broken in the time it takes a small bronze bell to ring twice. The patience is the suffering. The release, when it comes, is a sound." },
        "The saint waded out to them. He baptized them. They asked for it. They had time, in the water, to forgive Aoife — Fionnuala did, anyway, and the others followed her — and they died within minutes of one another, their old bodies giving up the ghost they had been holding at the door for so long, and the saint buried them in a single grave by the lake-shore: the three brothers in a row, and Fionnuala laid across them with her arms around their shoulders, the way she had slept across them as a child."
    ]
},

{
    id: "cu-chulainn",
    title: "Cú Chulainn's Final Stand",
    subtitle: "The hound of Ulster, lashed to a stone, fighting until the raven came",
    civilization: "celtic",
    themes: ["Fate", "Honor", "Battle-frenzy", "Standing"],
    content: [
        "He had been called Setanta when he was a child, but at the age of seven he had killed the great hound of the smith Culann — killed it with his bare hands, when it had attacked him in the dark — and he had offered, in apology, to take the hound's place at the smith's gate until a new pup could be raised. They had called him Cú Chulainn after that, the Hound of Culann, and the name had stuck the way a true name does, and he had grown up into the greatest warrior the kingdom of Ulster had ever known.",
        "He was small for a warrior. He had seven pupils in each eye. When the battle-frenzy came on him — the ríastrad, the warp-spasm — his body would invert itself, his joints would reverse, one eye would sink into his head and the other would extrude, his hair would stand stiff with a drop of blood at the tip of each strand, and the heat that came off him would melt the snow for ten yards in any direction. After such a frenzy three vats of cold water had to be readied for him: he would jump into the first and the water would boil away, into the second and it would simmer and steam, and into the third and only there would the heat be drawn out of him, and he would stand up shivering and cool and a man again.",
        "He had been, more than once, the only thing standing between Ulster and its enemies. He had held the ford at Ath Fhirdiad against an army for months, fighting one warrior a day in single combat. He had killed his foster-brother Ferdiad there, and he had wept all the next day on the bank. He had killed his own only son, Connla — not knowing the boy was his own, until afterwards — and he had wept for that, too, and the wound under his ribs from his son's spear never properly healed, and he had been carrying it around for years.",
        "Now he was thirty-three years old, perhaps thirty-four, which was old for a warrior of his sort. The geis on him — the small private prohibitions that bound every warrior of his rank — had begun to crowd him. He had been forbidden, since boyhood, to refuse food offered by a woman. He had been forbidden, also, to eat the meat of his namesake, the hound. He had spent his life walking carefully around these contradictions. The day came when they were laid against each other.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Queen Medb of Connacht — who had been his enemy for years, who had not forgiven him the long fight at the ford — sent against him three witch-women, daughters of a dead enemy. They sat by the road on which he had to ride to a battle, and they roasted, on a small fire, the haunch of a dog. They called out to him as he passed, courteously: \"Cú Chulainn. Sit. Eat with us.\"",
        "He paused. He saw what was on the spit. He understood the trap. To accept was to break one geis. To refuse the food of women was to break the other. There was no third path.",
        "He chose to break the smaller. He dismounted. He took a piece of the dog-meat. The witch-women smiled. The hand he had taken it with — his left, his shield-hand — went numb. The numbness ran up his arm. By the time he had remounted, the strength of half his body had left him.",
        "He rode on. He came to the field where the army of Medb was waiting for him. He fought anyway. He killed many.",
        "The chieftain of the enemy — a man named Lugaid — held a magical spear, the Gáe Bolg of his own crafting, and he called out, mockingly, in the manner of warriors, \"Whom shall this spear strike?\" and his druid called back, \"It will strike the king of Ireland!\" and Lugaid hurled it at Cú Chulainn, who was no king. But the spear struck the chariot, and from the chariot it leaped into Cú Chulainn's belly. His chariot-driver Láeg was killed by the next throw. The horses, struck in turn, took the chariot off the field at a stagger.",
        "He was alone now. He was bleeding from the belly. He had only one good arm. He could no longer ride.",
        "He did not fall.",
        "He walked, holding his guts in with one hand, to a tall stone in the middle of the plain, called the Stone of Cluiche. He took off his belt. He used the belt to lash himself, upright, to the stone. He propped his sword in his good hand. He turned his face toward the enemy.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The enemy did not approach. They waited. They had been told all their lives that this man was a force of nature; they could not be sure, even bleeding and lashed, that he was finished. Hours passed. He stood at the stone. The crows began to gather, smelling the blood, but even the crows kept their distance.",
        "At last a single great raven came down. The raven landed on his shoulder. The raven took, as ravens do, one small mouthful from his neck. He did not flinch. The raven took a second. He did not flinch. He had been bound to the stone now for so long that his blood had soaked the rope, his blood had soaked the stone, his blood had soaked the grass at his feet, and he had stopped, at some point, being a man with a body and become only a posture, a will, an upright thing in the sun.",
        "The enemy understood. They came forward, slowly, in a wide ring. Lugaid stepped up. He took Cú Chulainn's head. The body, even then, did not fall — it stayed upright on the rope.",
        "Lugaid stepped back, holding the severed head. He felt, for an instant, glory. Then the head — still warm — gave a small twitch of its lip and a small spark went out of its eye, and the sword in the dead man's good hand swung once, by some last reflex, and took Lugaid's hand off at the wrist. The sword fell. The hand fell. The head fell. The body, at last, slid down the rope. The Hound of Ulster was finished.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are some men who will not lie down even after they are killed. They lash themselves to the standing stones of their countries and refuse, on principle, to be measured horizontally. The dignity is the whole story." },
        "They built a cairn over him on the plain. The grass came back. The crows returned to their rookery. The kingdom of Ulster, freed of its great defender, did what kingdoms do — it forgot, slowly, what such a defender had cost — but the stone he had lashed himself to is still in the field, and the long shadow it throws at evening still has, the country people will tell you, the rough shape of a small man standing upright on a hill."
    ]
},

{
    id: "etain",
    title: "The Wooing of Étaín",
    subtitle: "A love that survived being turned into a fly and a thousand-year wind",
    civilization: "celtic",
    themes: ["Reincarnation", "Jealousy", "Transformation", "Destiny"],
    content: [
        "There was a king of the Tuatha Dé Danann named Midir, and Midir loved a woman named Étaín. She had been the daughter of a small chieftain by a faraway river. Midir had seen her once and had not been able to look at any other woman afterwards. He brought her into his hall on the green hill of Brí Léith. He gave her gold cups and a chamber lit by long beeswax candles and a soft bed, and he sat beside her at evenings and forgot to eat.",
        "Midir had a first wife. Her name was Fúamnach. She had been with him for centuries — for the gods of Ireland counted their marriages in centuries — and she was not pleased to see a young woman take the seat next to her husband at the long table. She made no scene. She smiled. She was warm to Étaín. She braided her hair for her once. She was, the household thought, very gracious about it. They were wrong.",
        "Fúamnach was a druidess. She had powers. She bided her time. One morning, when Midir was out riding, she came into Étaín's chamber alone. She held a wand of rowan-wood. She struck Étaín lightly on the shoulder.",
        "Étaín became a pool of water, in the middle of the floor, perfectly still.",
        "Fúamnach, satisfied, called for the stewards to come and mop up the spill. The stewards brought rags. They mopped. The pool, of its own quiet self, became steam, and the steam coiled up into the rafters, and out of the steam — slowly, because the working was not yet finished — there began to coalesce a small bright purple insect, a fly, with wings the color of a lit window. The fly had Étaín's mind in it. The fly was Étaín still.",
        "She buzzed in the rafters. Fúamnach smiled. \"Now,\" she said softly, \"now you may keep your husband's heart, my dear. But you'll keep it from up there.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Midir came home. He found his wife gone and his first wife smiling. He searched the house. He searched the hill. He did not find her.",
        "But the fly — Étaín-the-fly — flew down to him. It landed on the rim of his cup. It crawled up his thumb. It buzzed at his ear in a particular way that he understood, after a moment, was a voice, and the voice was hers. He understood at once what had happened. He let out a cry. He stretched out his hand. The fly settled on his palm.",
        "He kept her with him after that. He took her with him everywhere. She slept on his pillow. She drank from the cup he drank from. The household stopped asking. The household understood. He was, more or less, married to a fly. He was, also, more or less, happy in it, because she was still herself.",
        "Fúamnach saw the arrangement. She raised her wand again. She summoned a great wind — a wind that rose in the southwest and tore through the hill — and the wind picked up the bright purple fly and bore her out of the hall and away across the country. She blew for seven years. She had no place to land. She was thrown across mountains and bogs and the flat plains of the midlands. She did not die. She could not die. But she could not light, either, on anything for long.",
        "After seven years she fell, exhausted, into the cup of a chieftain's wife in a faraway kingdom. The wife, lifting the cup, swallowed her without seeing. Nine months later the wife gave birth to a daughter. They named the daughter Étaín. She was the same Étaín. She did not, this time, remember.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The new Étaín grew up. She was beautiful. She had a haunted quality to her, as if she was always almost remembering something she could not quite catch the shape of. She was, when she came of age, married to the high king of Ireland — a mortal king — and she became his queen, and she lived in his stone hall in Tara, and she had a quiet life, by the standards of her old life. She was happy enough. She did not know what she did not know.",
        "Midir, on his green hill, had not stopped looking. He had searched for a thousand years and a little more. He was a god; he had a thousand years to spend. He came at last, in disguise, to Tara. He came in the form of a tall stranger with one strange eye, and he asked the high king for a single board-game.",
        "The king agreed. He liked board-games. They played. The stranger lost the first round politely. He let the king win a small cup. They played again. The stranger lost again, this time a horse. They played a third time. The king grew confident. He let the stake be larger. \"What do you ask if you win?\" the stranger said.",
        "\"Anything that is mine,\" said the king carelessly.",
        "They played. The king lost. He had been letting his guard down. The stranger smiled.",
        "\"I will take,\" the stranger said, \"a single embrace from your queen, in front of the whole court, with her own consent. That is all.\"",
        "The king blanched. But he had agreed. He could not unagree, in front of his court, without becoming small in their eyes. He summoned Étaín. She came. The stranger bowed to her. He stepped close. He said something to her in a voice that no one else could hear, in a language that no one else knew. Étaín's eyes widened. She remembered. She remembered everything. The pool on the floor of Brí Léith, the bright purple wing, the wind, the seven years, the cup, the slow waking of a child who was a queen who had been a fly who had been a god's bride. She put her arms around Midir's neck.",
        "He embraced her. The two of them rose into the air. They went up through the smoke-hole of Tara as two white swans, joined at the neck by a chain of gold. They flew north. The king and his court ran out into the courtyard and watched the two white shapes diminish against the cold blue, and the king put his hands over his face, and his court understood that this had been a thing larger than him, larger than any of them, larger than the rooms in which they lived.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Some loves last so many lifetimes that they keep finding each other through transformations and forgettings, and the recognition, when it finally comes, is a remembering older than the bodies it lights up." },
        "And in the green hill of Brí Léith, Midir set Étaín on her old chair, and the candles were lit again — they had been kept by an old housekeeper who had refused to put them out — and Fúamnach, when she came into the hall to see, gave a single small cry and ran out into the night, and the house, after a thousand years of unfinishing, was finally itself again."
    ]
}
);


window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "ocean-of-milk",
    title: "The Churning of the Ocean of Milk",
    subtitle: "How gods and demons turned the sea together for the nectar of deathlessness",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["Cooperation", "Cosmic struggle", "Nectar", "Treasures"],
    content: [
        "The gods, in those days, were not yet immortal. They lived a long time. They lived longer than the brightest mortal in his brightest line. But they aged, slowly, the way mountains age, and they grew tired, and they could be killed, and they had been losing fights to the asuras — the elder cousins, called demons in some retellings, though that is a coarse word for what they were — and the cosmos was beginning to tilt.",
        "Indra, king of the gods, came to Vishnu, the preserver, and laid his heavy crown on the ground between them and asked for help. Vishnu, who was a god of long views, sat in thought a while. Then he said, \"There is a solution, but you will not like it. You will have to share the work with the asuras themselves, and at the end of the work share the prize. Or pretend to share it. There is, deep in the milk-white ocean of the south, a thing called amrita — the nectar of deathlessness. Whoever drinks it will not die. We must churn the ocean to bring it up.\"",
        "\"Churn,\" said Indra. \"Churn an ocean.\"",
        "\"You will need a mountain for the churn,\" said Vishnu. \"You will need a serpent for the rope. You will need every god and every asura, and you will pull together, and the ocean will give up what it has been keeping.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They went out and uprooted Mount Mandara — the gods on one side, the asuras on the other, both straining together — and they brought it to the shore of the milk-white ocean. They tipped it into the water. The mountain began to sink. They were aghast. Vishnu, calm, became a great turtle — Kurma — and slid himself under the mountain's base, and the mountain settled on his immense patient back, and the churning could begin.",
        "They needed a rope. They went to Vasuki, the great serpent, who was so long that his head was a country away from his tail, and they asked. Vasuki agreed. They wound him around the mountain. The asuras, being proud, demanded the head end of the snake — they did not want to be made to hold the lower end, the tail end, which they considered demeaning. The gods agreed politely. They took the tail.",
        "They began to pull. The asuras pulled the head, and then the gods pulled the tail, and then the asuras pulled, and then the gods pulled, and the great mountain spun on the back of the great turtle, and the great ocean churned, and the milk became foam, and the foam became cloud, and the cloud became a long slow stirring of every fortune the deep had been keeping for a billion years.",
        "But Vasuki, churned and pulled by his head, began to suffer, and out of his mouth came a poison — Halahala, the deepest dark, a venom so black that wherever it landed it ate the world to nothing. The poison began to spill. It threatened to ruin everything before the churning had finished.",
        "Shiva — the destroyer, who is also the gentle god of last resort — stepped forward. He cupped his hands. He gathered the spilled poison. He drank it. His wife Parvati, in horror, clamped her hands around his throat to stop the poison from going down into his belly, and the poison stopped at his neck, and his throat turned blue forever, and that is why Shiva is sometimes called the Blue-Throated, and you can know him by it.",
        "The churning continued.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Out of the milk-white ocean came treasures, one after another, gifts from the deep that had not been taken into the world yet.",
        "First came Surabhi, the wish-cow, who could give whatever was asked of her, and the cow walked up onto the shore and grazed peacefully, as if she had been there always.",
        "Then came Uchchaihshravas, a horse white as cloud, with seven heads and a wind in his mane, and the horse galloped along the beach without a rider.",
        "Then came Airavata, an elephant white as mountain-snow, with four tusks and a back broad enough to carry the king of the gods, and Indra reached for him at once.",
        "Then came Kalpavriksha, the wishing-tree, planted itself on the shore.",
        "Then came Lakshmi, the goddess of fortune, riding up out of the foam on a white lotus, dressed in red and gold, and every god and every asura, seeing her, drew breath, but she walked up the white sand and put her garland over Vishnu, and that was the choice she made, and the gods cheered and the asuras grumbled.",
        "Then came Chandra, the moon, cool and round, and Shiva took the moon and tucked it into his hair.",
        "Then came Varuni, the goddess of wine, and the asuras took her, because they wanted at least something.",
        "And then — last, finally, what they had been turning the ocean for — came Dhanvantari, the divine physician, walking up out of the foam with a small white pot in his two hands. The pot was the amrita. The pot was the nectar of deathlessness. The two armies surged forward at once.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The asuras seized the pot. They turned and ran. They were closer; they had been waiting; they were faster, in the moment of grabbing, than the gods had been ready for. The gods were aghast. If the asuras drank, the war was over forever, in their disfavor.",
        "Vishnu — who had a long view of these things — became, briefly, a woman. He became Mohini, who was so beautiful that the asuras, even running with the pot in their hands, slowed and stopped and stared. Mohini walked up to them and held out a slender hand. \"Let me serve,\" she said softly. \"You will fight over it. I will be fair. I will pour for the gods first, then for you. Or for you first, then the gods. Whichever you prefer. Just sit. Just sit and be served.\"",
        "The asuras, dazzled, sat down in two long rows. Mohini took the pot. She walked along the rows of the gods, pouring small careful sips into each god's cupped hand, and each god, sipping, became immortal, and the gods began to glow in the late afternoon light.",
        "An asura named Rahu, suspicious, slipped into the line of the gods. He sat between the sun and the moon. Mohini, distracted by her grace, poured into his hand. He drank. The sun and the moon — both of whom were gods — saw it happen, and they cried out, and Mohini turned, and Vishnu's discus came spinning out of nowhere, and it took the asura's head from his shoulders. But the nectar had already touched his throat. The head was immortal. The body was not. The body fell. The head rolled and lived.",
        "And from that day Rahu — only a head — has chased the sun and the moon across the sky, and sometimes he catches one of them in his jaws, and we look up and see the eclipse, and the eclipse is the small daily resentment of an asura who almost beat the system.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There is no easy nectar. The deepest sweetness comes only after a poison has been swallowed, after a turtle has held a mountain, after a serpent has been pulled in two directions, after the patient ones have stayed at the work long enough to deserve what rises." },
        "The gods, immortal now, drove the asuras back into their lower country. The cosmos righted itself. But the asuras, for the rest of forever, would remember that they too had pulled, that they too had spun the mountain, and that they had been promised half — and the long resentment of that broken half-promise has driven a great deal of the trouble in every age since."
    ]
},

{
    id: "krishna-kaliya",
    title: "Krishna and the Serpent Kaliya",
    subtitle: "A boy-god dances on the heads of the river's tyrant",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["River", "Cleansing", "Dance", "Mercy"],
    content: [
        "There was a river called the Yamuna, which ran cold and green through the land of Vraja, and on the banks of the Yamuna grew long grass where cattle liked to graze, and along its bends the cowherd-boys of the village played their flutes and threw stones into the slow eddies and waded in the shallows. The Yamuna was a good river. It had been a good river for a long time.",
        "But for some time now the Yamuna had been not good. There was a deep dark pool below a tall mulberry tree, and the pool boiled at all hours, and the fish in it were dead, and the birds that flew over it fell from the air, and the cattle would not drink from any part of the river within a mile of it. The pool had been taken. A serpent named Kaliya — five heads, body the color of a thundercloud, venom so strong it had made the water poisonous for a country in every direction — had come up from the lower country and made the pool his lair. Kaliya was full of arrogance. He had been driven out of his old home by Garuda, the great eagle of the gods, and he had come here to sulk and to spread his influence outward.",
        "The cowherd-boys had been losing cattle. They had been losing one of themselves now and again, when a thirsty boy ran to drink without thinking. The village had been in mourning so often that mourning had become its weather.",
        "Krishna was eight years old at the time, or perhaps nine. He was a cowherd-boy himself. He was also a god, in a small dark blue body that did not let on more than was strictly necessary, and his foster-mother braided butter into his hair every morning and laughed at the trouble he got into and did not always understand who she was raising.",
        "He went out one day to the deep pool of Kaliya. He climbed the mulberry tree at the bank. He stood on a high branch and looked at the boiling water. He took a long breath. He jumped.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The water of the pool exploded around him. He went down and down and the green of the surface vanished above him and he kept going, and at the bottom of the pool he found Kaliya — coiled, pale-bellied, the five great heads swaying, the eyes shining the color of bad lamp-oil. The serpent saw the small dark blue boy descending and could not at first understand what he was seeing. Then he laughed, with all five mouths.",
        "He struck. He wrapped Krishna in his coils. He bit the boy's shoulder. He tightened.",
        "On the bank above, the cowherds — who had followed Krishna, terrified, calling — began to weep. The water shook. Bubbles came up. The pool went still. They thought he was gone.",
        "But under the water Krishna had begun to grow. He grew as he had grown before, when his mother had once tried to look into his small mouth and had seen the universe inside it instead. He grew until the coils that had wrapped him were straining, and then he grew further, and Kaliya — astonished, alarmed — uncoiled and floated back, and the five heads reared up with wide eyes.",
        "The boy stood on the river-bed and laughed, and then the boy — without effort, almost playfully — leaped onto the central head of the serpent and began to dance.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He danced.",
        "He had small bare feet, and they came down on the head of Kaliya as lightly as a butter-thief steps on the kitchen floor — but each step was the weight of a god, and each step pressed the great head down into the river-mud. He moved from one head to another. He kept time. The cowherds on the bank, when they saw what was happening — for the boiling had subsided, and the water had gone clear, and they could see down — wept again, and this time they wept for joy, and they began to clap. They began to clap a rhythm. The boy danced to the rhythm of the clapping. The serpent's heads, one by one, sank under the dancing of the boy's feet.",
        "Each time a head bent under, Kaliya coughed up a great mouthful of his venom into the water, and the venom — which had been in him, festering, for a long time — was thus expelled, drained out of him, drained out into the river, where it glittered briefly black and then dissolved.",
        "Kaliya understood, dimly, that he was being killed. The wives of Kaliya — for he had wives, several of them, naga-women, soft-eyed, terrified — came up out of the deeper rocks and threw themselves on the river-bed in front of Krishna and folded their hands.",
        "\"Lord,\" they said, \"forgive him. He was vain. He has been beaten. He understands now. Please.\"",
        "Krishna stopped dancing. He stood with one foot still on the central head. He looked down at the serpent. The serpent's eye, which had been the color of bad lamp-oil, was the color now of an exhausted dog's. The serpent could not speak — his mouths were full of mud — but he made a small bowing motion with his neck, and Krishna nodded.",
        "\"Go,\" he said. \"You will not stay here. You will return to the deep ocean — your old country — and you will not come back. I have left a mark on each of your heads. Garuda will see the mark when he hunts you, and he will know you are mine, and he will let you pass. Tell him that. He will respect it.\"",
        "Kaliya, with what was left of him, bowed all five heads. The wives wept gratitude. The serpent uncoiled. The serpent and his wives swam, slow, down the river toward the sea, and they did not stop until they had reached water that knew nothing of cattle or boys.",
        "Krishna rose from the bottom of the pool and broke the surface like a small dark blue lotus. The cowherds dragged him out by both arms. They could not stop touching him. His foster-mother, when she got him home, scolded him for an hour for his ruined clothes and put him to bed and only then sat down by the fire and let herself shake.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The dance that drives out a tyrant does not have to be a stamping. The lightest foot, kept in time, kept patient, on the right head, can press a king down into the mud and ask only that he leave." },
        "And the river afterwards ran clean again. The fish came back. The cattle drank without dying. And on certain summer afternoons, when the wind moved on the water, you could see the small ripples that looked, almost, like the prints of a child's bare feet, faintly dancing on the surface."
    ]
},

{
    id: "ganga",
    title: "The Descent of Ganga",
    subtitle: "How a king's penance brought the sky-river to earth, caught in a god's hair",
    civilization: "hindu",
    themes: ["River", "Penance", "Sacrifice", "Earth"],
    content: [
        "There was once a king named Sagara, and Sagara had sixty thousand sons. The number was a literal number; the queen had made an arrangement with a sage, and the result was a small army of princes, all of them strong, all of them proud, none of them especially humble. Sagara conducted a great horse-sacrifice, in which a sacred horse was let loose to wander, and wherever it wandered the king claimed sovereignty, and at the end of a year the horse would be brought home and offered, and the king would be ruler of every land it had touched.",
        "But the horse went missing. Indra, who had grown jealous, had stolen it. He hid it in the hermitage of a sage named Kapila, deep in the lower country. The sixty thousand sons set out to find the horse. They searched the world above. They did not find it. They began to dig. They dug downward. Sixty thousand princes digging — the earth shook for years. They dug into the lower country. They came at last to the cave where the sage Kapila was sitting in meditation, and beside him stood the horse, peacefully grazing on the grass that grew on the cave-floor.",
        "The princes did not pause to consider. They began to abuse the sage. \"Thief! You stole our father's horse!\" The sage opened his eyes. He had been deep in meditation; the centuries of inward labor were heavy in his eye. He looked at them. The look was simply the look. The sixty thousand princes were burnt to ash, all at once, where they stood, and the ash piled around the cave-floor, and the horse, undisturbed, kept eating its grass.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "King Sagara grew old without his sons. The line continued in a single grandson, Anshuman, and then a great-grandson, Dilipa, and then a great-great-grandson, Bhagiratha. Each king of that long line carried the same private knowledge: that sixty thousand of his ancestors lay as ash in a cave below the world, unfinished, unburied, their souls neither risen nor settled, because their funeral rites had never been performed.",
        "There was only one thing that could complete those rites. The river Ganga — the holy river that flowed in the high heaven — was the only water in which their ash could properly be washed, and only its washing would lift them from the bondage of their unfinished deaths. But the Ganga ran in heaven. There was no way to reach her from below. The ancestors could not be saved unless someone could persuade the river to come down.",
        "The earlier kings had each tried penance. Each had failed. The river had not heard them. Or, if she had heard, she had not been moved.",
        "Bhagiratha set out to do what the others had not done. He left his throne. He went into the deep forest. He built a fire. He sat beside it. He fasted. He prayed, with his arms held above his head, for years on end. The forest grew up around him. Vines wrapped his ankles. Birds nested in his beard. He did not move. He did not speak. He held the river's name in his mind without letting it out of his mind, day after day, year after year, and at last — at last — Ganga heard.",
        "She came. She appeared above him in the air, blue-white and laughing, with her hair the color of foam.",
        "\"You wish me to come down,\" she said.",
        "\"I wish you to come down.\"",
        "\"You understand,\" she said gently, \"that if I come down with my full weight, I will shatter the earth. The earth has not been built to receive me. I am the river of heaven. I will fall as a single column of water from the sky to the floor of the world, and where I land there will be nothing — no soil, no rock, no city, no mountain. The world will be split.\"",
        "\"Then,\" said Bhagiratha, \"we must find someone who can catch you.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Bhagiratha began a second penance. This one was directed at Shiva — the destroyer, the meditator, the one who had drunk poison for the gods, the only being in the cosmos who might have the strength to absorb the river's fall.",
        "Shiva heard. Shiva agreed. He was, in his quiet way, fond of Bhagiratha. He stood at the appointed time on the high white peak of Kailasa, with his eyes closed and his arms folded and his long matted hair piled up on his head in the way of an ascetic. He waited.",
        "Ganga descended.",
        "She came down out of heaven in a roar. She had decided, at the last moment, to come hard — harder than necessary, perhaps with a small intention of breaking through Shiva and continuing on, of showing that no god above could stand between a sky-river and her course. She fell.",
        "Shiva did not move. He did not stagger. The full weight of the heavenly river, falling at the speed of all of heaven, struck the top of his head, and his hair caught it. The matted locks of Shiva — long, twisted, immense — opened like a forest of ropes, and the river of heaven entered them, and the river of heaven could not get out again. She wandered through the labyrinth of his hair, lost. She could not find a way down to the earth. She could not find a way back up to the sky. She wandered. She wept.",
        "Bhagiratha, on the slopes below, could see no river. Only the silent god on the peak, with the strange faint glimmering above his head where the trapped water flowed.",
        "He began a third penance. He sat. He prayed. He prayed to Shiva to let her down — to relent, to soften, to allow a single thread of the river out of his hair to make its way to earth. Years passed. He did not stop. At last Shiva, again moved, opened a single lock of his matted hair and let a single strand of the river out.",
        "It came down the slopes of Kailasa as a thin clear stream. It grew as it went. By the time it had crossed the foothills it was a true river. Bhagiratha, weeping, walked at its head, and the river followed him, polite as a guest behind her host. He led her down through the plains. He led her along the route to the lower country. The river followed his every step.",
        "On the way, the river accidentally flooded the hermitage of a sage named Jahnu, who, irritated, drank her up entirely. Bhagiratha had to undertake a fourth penance — to apologize to Jahnu, to ask him to release her — and Jahnu, after a while, released her through his ear, and the river continued, and from that day she was also called Jahnavi, the daughter of Jahnu, in remembrance of the small detour.",
        "She came at last to the cave under the lower country, where the sixty thousand piles of ash had lain so long that they had grown a light gray dust on top. Bhagiratha stood aside. The river ran in. The ash dissolved. The souls of the sixty thousand princes — released at last from the weightless grief of unfinished rites — rose like a flock of bright birds and went up into the high country where the ancestors are at peace, and the cave was empty for the first time in five generations.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Some debts take five lifetimes of patience to pay. Some rivers must be coaxed out of heaven a thread at a time. The work of releasing what is owed to the dead is done in long quiet years by people who do not see the end of their own labor." },
        "The river did not return to heaven. She stayed. She still flows through the plains, and her waters carry, the priests say, the same purifying power that lifted the sixty thousand. People stand in her at dawn with cupped hands. They send their dead to her. The river accepts them. She has never said no since."
    ]
}
);


window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "amaterasu",
    title: "Amaterasu in the Cave of Heaven",
    subtitle: "How a goddess was coaxed back into the sky by laughter",
    civilization: "japanese",
    themes: ["Sun", "Sister-rivalry", "Light", "Mirror"],
    content: [
        "Amaterasu, who was the sun, had a brother. His name was Susanoo, and he was the storm. Their father had divided the rule of the world between his children — sun-sister to the sky, storm-brother to the sea — and Susanoo had not taken the assignment well. He had wanted his mother. His mother was in the underworld. He had cried, because he was a god and gods can cry, and his crying had killed crops over half the country and dried up rivers and torn up forests in the wind that came with the weeping. The high gods had at last told him to stop. They had banished him to the underworld in his turn.",
        "But before he went he wanted to say goodbye to his sister.",
        "He went up to the high plain where Amaterasu lived. He came up making a noise like a typhoon. The mountains shook. The trees on the slopes leaned away from him. Amaterasu, looking down from her terrace, saw her brother coming and did not believe his story; she thought he was coming to take her kingdom. She put on her armor. She bound up her hair like a man's. She drew a bow as long as she was tall, and she stood in the middle of her courtyard with her feet planted, and she challenged him.",
        "He said he came in peace. She said prove it. They held a contest of children-making. From their offerings each made gods. They quarreled afterwards over which of them had won, the way brothers and sisters quarrel — over a thing that had not, at the start, been quite the thing. He laughed at the end and said, See, I am peaceful, my children are gentle children. And then, exuberant, victorious, exhausted, he ran riot. He broke the dikes of the rice-paddies. He filled the irrigation channels with mud. He defecated on the floor of the great hall. And finally — the worst of it, the unforgivable of it — he flayed a heavenly horse and threw the skinned body through the roof of the weaving-hall, where one of Amaterasu's handmaidens was at her loom, and the handmaiden, struck by the falling shuttle as she leaped back, was killed.",
        "Amaterasu did not yell. She did not weep. She did not strike him. She rose without a word, walked out of the wrecked hall, and went down to the cave at the foot of the mountain. She walked into the cave. She rolled the great stone across the mouth.",
        "And the world went black.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "It was midmorning when she did it. The sun simply stopped. Birds, mid-song, fell silent. Cattle in the fields did not know whether to lie down or stand. Mothers nursing infants felt the milk slow in them. The plants, which had been turning their faces upward, stopped turning. The rice did not finish growing. The crickets, who had not had a chance to sing yet, began to sing, in confusion, in the wrong hour. The wrong hour had become the only hour. There was no longer any hour.",
        "Demons, who in those days had been content to keep to the dark places, came out into the long unbroken dark. They walked through villages by daylight, which was no longer daylight. People closed their doors. People wept. The country went to ruin in three days.",
        "The eight million gods convened a council on the dry bed of the river of heaven. They talked. They argued. They tried prayers. They tried offerings. The cave did not open. They tried wailing — a great organized wailing — at the cave's mouth. Amaterasu, behind the stone, did not move. The hurt was a real hurt. They needed her, but they did not get to dictate the terms.",
        "It was Ame-no-Uzume who solved it.",
        "Ame-no-Uzume was a goddess of dawn and of dance and of mirth. She was small. She was loud. She was famously immune to dignity. She ordered a great brazen bath-tub overturned in front of the cave for a stage. She gathered roosters — a great noisy assemblage of them — to crow at the cave mouth, because their crowing was the morning, and perhaps if there was crowing there would be morning. The eight million gods stood in a half-ring, holding torches, holding curiosity.",
        "Ame-no-Uzume climbed onto the upturned tub.",
        "She bound her sleeves up. She tucked the hem of her dress into her sash. She began to dance. She stamped on the bronze and it boomed like a drum. She kicked her legs in the air. She laughed. She made faces that even the dignified gods of the council could not, in good conscience, look at without laughing. She loosened her sash entirely, and the dress came open, and she did not stop the dance, and the eight million gods burst into a roar of laughter so loud that it cracked the sky.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "In the cave Amaterasu lifted her head.",
        "She had been weeping in the dark. She had been certain, in her grief, that the world above was suffering — yes — but suffering with the dignity of mourning. She had not expected laughter. She had not expected what sounded, in fact, like a great party.",
        "She rolled the stone aside a finger's width and put her eye to the crack.",
        "Outside, the gods, who had been waiting for exactly this, had set up a great bronze mirror so that it caught the small sliver of light from the crack and threw it back into her face. She saw a brilliance she did not know was her own. \"Who is the new sun?\" she said, blinking. \"Who has dared to take my office?\"",
        "Ame-no-Uzume, on the tub, said cheerfully, \"There is a new goddess, much brighter than you, here above. We are celebrating.\"",
        "Amaterasu, indignant — and curious, very curious — pushed the stone wider. She leaned out. The two strongest gods, Tajikarao and another, who had been waiting for exactly this, took the great stone and hurled it away forever, and grabbed her by the wrists, and pulled her gently out into the air.",
        "And the world was bright again.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Sometimes the way to bring a god back into the world is to put on a noisy, undignified joy at her doorstep, and to set up a mirror so that she can see, sideways, what a brilliant thing she has been all along." },
        "They sealed the cave behind her with a sacred rope of rice-straw, the shimenawa, so that she could not return there. The roosters, who had been crowing the whole time, fell silent at last in their satisfied way. Susanoo was banished, properly this time, to the lower country. And Amaterasu, who had known sorrow now, took up her sun-disk again and walked back across the high plain to her terrace, where the dishes from the long-broken party were still on the table, but where the day was, again, a day."
    ]
},

{
    id: "susanoo-orochi",
    title: "Susanoo and the Eight-Headed Serpent",
    subtitle: "An exiled storm-god finds his redemption in a sword pulled from a tail",
    civilization: "japanese",
    themes: ["Storm", "Monster-slaying", "Sword", "Atonement"],
    content: [
        "After his banishment from heaven for the wrecking of his sister's halls, Susanoo wandered the lower world for a long while. He was not invited anywhere. The wind that had once attended him kept its distance. He grew quieter, the way a storm grows quiet after it has had its night and learned, hung-over, what it has done.",
        "He came at last to a river in the country of Izumo, and he sat down on the bank to wash, because he was tired and dirty. As he sat, a chopstick floated past on the water. He looked at it. People upstream, he thought. Where there are chopsticks there are people. He stood up and began to walk against the current.",
        "He came to a low house among willows. From inside the house came the sound of weeping — not one voice but three. He pushed the screen open. Inside sat an old man, an old woman, and between them a young woman of perhaps eighteen, very beautiful, weeping into her sleeves.",
        "\"Why do you weep?\" Susanoo asked.",
        "The old man rose and bowed deeply. \"We had eight daughters,\" he said, his voice thin. \"Each year a great serpent comes up out of the river, the Yamata-no-Orochi, with eight heads and eight tails, and each year he has demanded one of our daughters. Tonight he comes for the last. Her name is Kushinada-hime. She is all that is left to us.\"",
        "Susanoo looked at the young woman. She looked back. She did not lower her eyes. There was a steadiness in her, even through the tears, that he had not expected.",
        "\"If I save her,\" he said, \"will you give her to me as my wife?\"",
        "The old man and old woman fell on their faces. They would have given her to a beggar at this point. Susanoo lifted them up and asked the more useful question. \"What does the serpent like?\"",
        "\"Drink,\" said the old man. \"He is fond of strong drink.\"",
        "\"Then make me strong drink,\" said Susanoo. \"Eight tubs of it. The strongest you can brew. And eight wooden barriers around your courtyard, with eight platforms along them, and on each platform a tub.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "They worked through the day. They brewed the rice-spirit eight times distilled, until each tub was a little well of fire. They built the eight barriers and the eight platforms. Susanoo, meanwhile, transformed Kushinada-hime — she was eighteen and steady and now also a small comb, and he tucked the comb into the knot of his hair, where the serpent could not reach her.",
        "Dusk came. The reeds at the river's edge began to shudder. Then the water began to shudder. Then the great heads came up — eight of them, on eight long necks, eyes the color of forge-coals, breath that smelled of iron and stagnant blood. The serpent, called Orochi, was so vast that his eight tails draped across eight valleys behind him, and on his back grew moss and ancient pines as if he were a hill that had taken a notion to walk.",
        "He came up over the bank. He came into the courtyard. He saw the eight tubs, and the eight noses lifted, and the eight pairs of eyes brightened with appetite. Each head bent to a tub. Each head began to drink.",
        "Susanoo stood very still in the shadow of a willow. He waited. He was patient, this time, in a way the storm had not always been patient. The eight heads drank deep. They drank deeper. They wavered. One head fell to the ground. Then another. Then all eight, slowly, like petals on a flower folding closed, sank to the wet stones of the courtyard.",
        "Then Susanoo drew his sword.",
        "He went to work. The first head he took at the throat. The second at the throat. The third at the throat. The serpent, drunk and dreaming, did not wake fully. The fourth, the fifth, the sixth, the seventh — every blow struck cleanly. The eighth he took last, looking into its dimming eye for an instant before he struck, because he wanted the serpent to know.",
        "Then he turned to the tails. He chopped them off, one by one, working back along the long body. On the eighth tail his sword broke.",
        "It broke clean across. He stared at it. He had a sword that broke on the tail of a serpent? He bent down. In the muscle of that eighth tail something was lodged. Something hard. He cut around it carefully. He pulled it out.",
        "It was a sword. It was a long sword, slender as a willow leaf, the metal of it the color of cloud, and the moment he held it he understood that it was a sword that had not existed in the world before, that the serpent had grown around it the way an oyster grows around a grain. The blade had a name already, in his head: Kusanagi, the Grass-Cutter.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He took the sword. He took the comb out of his hair and breathed on it, and Kushinada-hime stood up beside him, whole, and looked at the eight quiet tails of the serpent, and she did not faint.",
        "He sent the sword back up to heaven, to his sister Amaterasu, as a gift — an apology, in the only language gods send apologies, which is treasure. The sword passed down through her descendants. It is one of the three sacred regalia of Japan to this day. It is not on display. It is somewhere, in a shrine, wrapped in silk, kept by the priests, and the priests know where it is and they do not say.",
        "Susanoo stayed in Izumo. He built a hall. He married Kushinada-hime. They had children. He became, in time, the patron god of that country, and the wind in the willows on that river is, for those who can hear it, a quieter wind than it had been in his earlier years.",
        { style: "quote", text: "The atonement of a storm is not in the silencing of itself but in finding the right thing to break against. The sword the serpent had been keeping was not for the serpent. It was for the day after." },
        "The sword Kusanagi means \"Grass-Cutter,\" and it was named that not for its first deed but for its second — but that is another story, and Susanoo had nothing to do with it, having by then taken the long quiet that befits a god who has finally learned what to do with his weather."
    ]
},

{
    id: "otohime",
    title: "The Dragon Princess Otohime",
    subtitle: "Three days under the sea, three hundred years above it",
    civilization: "japanese",
    themes: ["Sea", "Time", "Promise", "Curiosity"],
    content: [
        "Urashima Tarō was a fisherman. He was not the most skilled fisherman in his village, nor the worst. He had been alone since his parents had died, and he lived in a small house with a single net. His habit was to go out on the water before dawn, to fish quietly, to come back at dusk, and to sit by his fire and read what little there was to read in his small house, and to sleep, and to do it all again.",
        "One day, walking along the beach, he came upon a knot of children tormenting a turtle. The turtle was small and brown and patient and had been turned on its back, and the children were poking at its underside with sticks and laughing. Urashima paid them off — handed them, from his small purse, a coin each — and they ran away whooping, and he set the turtle right side up and carried it down to the surf and put it gently back in the water. The turtle paused at the wave-line, looked back at him with its dark patient eye, and slipped under.",
        "He thought no more of it. He went home. He slept.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The next afternoon, far out at sea, he was leaning over the gunwale of his boat watching for the line to twitch when a turtle — much larger than the small one — surfaced beside the boat. \"Urashima,\" said the turtle, in a voice both polite and old, \"the princess of the sea wishes to thank you for your kindness yesterday. Will you come with me?\"",
        "Urashima, who was a quiet man unaccustomed to being addressed by turtles, said yes. He had no good reason. The afternoon was peaceful. He climbed out of his boat and onto the turtle's broad back, and the turtle dove.",
        "They went down. The water above closed over them. The light grew greener, and then greener still, and then bluer, and then dimmer, and then all of a sudden brighter than before — for they had come into the gardens of the dragon king's palace, called the Ryūgū-jō, where the light came not from above but from coral and pearl and the patient luminescence of the deep.",
        "The palace was enormous. It was built of red and white coral. The roofs were of thatched seaweed. The fish that flew through the corridors were of every color a fish has ever been. The gardens had four seasons, all at once — spring on the eastern path, summer on the southern, autumn on the western, winter on the northern — so that you could walk a single afternoon and see the cherry blossoms and the autumn maples and the snow on the pines and the wisteria all without leaving the grounds.",
        "Otohime, the dragon king's daughter, met him at the gate. She was not what he had imagined. She wore a dress of long sea-silk, and her hair was the color of polished slate, and her eyes were the color of the deep at noon. She had been the small turtle, the day before. She had wanted to see, herself, what kind of man he was. She had decided, on the basis of his rescue, that he was her kind of man.",
        "She gave him a feast. She showed him the four-seasoned garden. She showed him the great pearl-strung halls. She gave him days that ran into days, in a place where, since the light was the same in every hour, the days did not feel like days. He was not sure how long he had been there. He was, perhaps, very happy. It was hard to tell. The water-light has a quality of soft gentle suspension that is not quite the same as joy.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "After three days — or what he believed to be three days — he thought of his village. He thought of his small house. He thought, with a slow heaviness, of his mother, who had died in the back room of that house, and how he had not been there to read her sutras for her, and how it had been nine years and he should at least walk by the spot.",
        "He went to Otohime. He bowed. He said, \"I must go.\"",
        "She did not argue. Her people did not argue with the wishes of guests; that was their courtesy. She only said, gently, \"Do not return easily. Time is not the same here.\" And she gave him a gift to take home — a small lacquered box, very plain, tied with a red cord. \"Whatever you do,\" she said, putting both her hands over his on the box, \"do not open it. Do not open it for any reason. As long as you do not open it, you will be able to come back.\"",
        "He swore he would not. The turtle came again, and Urashima climbed on its back, and they went up. The water grew lighter. The water broke over his head. He stood in his boat in the sun, and the boat was the same boat. He rowed home.",
        "He came up the beach to his village.",
        "The village was the wrong village. The houses were in different places. The trees were larger than they had been. There were people he did not recognize. He went up to his street. His house was not there. There was a different house. He stopped a small girl. He asked, \"Where is the house of Urashima Tarō?\"",
        "She said, blinking, \"Urashima Tarō? My grandfather's grandfather used to talk about an Urashima Tarō. He went out one day in his boat and never came back. They thought he had drowned. It was three hundred years ago.\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He stood in the village street with the small lacquered box in his hands.",
        "Three hundred years.",
        "Everyone he had ever known was a name on a stone in a graveyard. The mother whose sutras he had wanted to read had been bone for centuries. The girl who had teased him as a boy had grown old, had died, had become a memory of a memory, and was nothing at all. He was alone in a way that no man before him had ever been alone.",
        "He sat down on a stone in the road. He looked at the box. He had been told not to open it. He had been told this very firmly. But Otohime, who had told him, was — was she even still alive? Did dragons live three hundred years? Of course they did. Of course she did. But the world he had stepped back into could no longer hold him, and the world he had come from no longer felt urgent, and his hands moved before his thinking did.",
        "He untied the red cord. He lifted the lid.",
        "A small white smoke rose out of the box. It was the time he had spent under the sea — three hundred years of it, kept folded inside the box, kept off him by her gift. The smoke rose around him, swirled past his face, and dispersed in the village air, and as it did his hair turned white in a single breath, and his back bent in a single breath, and his hands went brown and brittle, and he was three hundred years old at last, and the box fell from his fingers, and Urashima Tarō, who had been a fisherman, lay down on the stone and closed his eyes and joined his mother.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are gifts the gods give which are not for opening. There are kindnesses which require, in their keeping, a small disciplined ignorance. The man who must know what is in the box is the man who will not be able to live with what is in him afterward." },
        "Otohime, in the four-seasoned garden, felt the box open. She did not cry out. She had known, when she gave it, what she was risking, because love has always to risk what it gives. She walked alone, that afternoon, on the western path of the garden, where it was always autumn, and she sat under a maple, and she let the small red leaves fall on her hair, and the deep around her was very quiet."
    ]
}
);


window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.push(
{
    id: "yggdrasil",
    title: "Odin at the World-Tree",
    subtitle: "Nine nights nailed to himself for the price of letters",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Wisdom", "Sacrifice", "Self", "Runes"],
    content: [
        "There is a tree called Yggdrasil, and the tree is the spine of the world. Its roots go down into three wells: one in the kingdom of the gods, one in the kingdom of the giants, one in the kingdom of the dead. Its branches go up so high that the eagle who lives in the topmost crown has never seen the bottom and the dragon who gnaws the lowest root has never seen the sky. A squirrel, called Ratatosk, runs the long trunk every day to carry insults from one to the other. The tree shudders. The tree never falls.",
        "Hung from the tree, once, was a god. His own spear was driven through him. The blood ran along the bark and dried there in long dark stains. The wind moved his white hair. He hung there nine nights — long, slow, deliberate nights — and on the ninth night the runes came up out of the well at his feet and he reached down with his free hand and lifted them out of the water and into himself, and that was Odin, and that was how letters came into the world.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He had not been forced. There was no enemy. He had hung himself there. He was the god of wisdom and he had wanted more wisdom than he had, and the way to ask for what is not freely given, in the country of the North, is to put yourself out as the price.",
        "He had given other things before. He had given an eye, once, at the well of Mimir — paid it in for a single sip of the dark water, which had shown him the future, and the future was bad. He had given his sleep, more or less. He went out under his hat to the edges of the worlds in disguise, asking, asking, never getting back what he had spent.",
        "But the runes were the last and biggest payment. There were no letters yet. The names of things drifted in the air without anchor. A man could speak a name and have it lost again before sundown. Odin, the god of memory, could not bear that. He had decided that the world needed a way to keep its words. The runes were that. They were carved shapes — some angular, some forked, some like a man with arms outstretched — and each one had a sound and a power, and once they were caught they could be cut into a stone or a stick or a sword or a doorpost, and what was cut would not be lost.",
        "But the runes did not give themselves. They lived in the well. They had to be paid for in pain, because letters are made of pain, because every poem worth keeping was paid for in some shape by the singer, and the runes had decided long ago to demand at least one obvious bill before they came up.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "He hung. The first night, his feet went numb. He could not move them. The wind picked up. He composed an inward song to himself, which is what you do when there is nothing else to do. The second night his arms began to fail. The third night his thoughts grew sharp and slow, the way they do when there is no food in the body. The fourth night the ravens of the world — Huginn and Muninn, who were his — flew down and perched on the cross-piece beside him, one to each shoulder, and did not eat his eyes, because he had asked them not to. They watched. They waited with him.",
        "By the seventh night he was no longer entirely sure who he was. He was a long pale shape on a tree. The wind blew through him. By the ninth night he had become as light as a leaf, and the leaf had become as heavy as a stone, and the stone was nine nights of being a hung god, and below him the well was beginning to ripple.",
        "The runes came up.",
        "They came up slowly. They came up like fish coming up to a moonlit surface. He saw them — the angular shapes, the named noises — and he understood, in that hanging instant, every word that would ever be cut and every word that ever could be cut, and he reached down with the only hand that still moved and he took them.",
        "And he fell.",
        "He fell off the tree onto the wet root, and he lay there a while, and then he stood up, and he was a god of letters now as well as wisdom and rage and travel and war, and he took the runes up to the high seat of the gods and he taught them, slowly, to anyone who would listen, and the world began at last to keep its names.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Wisdom is not a thing that is given. It is a thing that is paid for, and the bill comes due in advance, and you have to be the one who pays it. The god who would not have hung himself is not a god you would have asked." },
        "He bore the marks of those nine nights for the rest of forever. The single eye, given separately at the well, was not the worst of his missing pieces. The deeper missing piece was something interior, and he carried it like a guttered candle that he had once let burn all the way down, on purpose, to see what kind of light came up when there was no wax left to burn."
    ]
},

{
    id: "fenrir",
    title: "The Binding of Fenrir",
    subtitle: "How the gods bought time, and what it cost a hand",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Fate", "Trust", "Betrayal", "Foreknowledge"],
    content: [
        "Loki — clever Loki, half-giant, friend of the gods until he wasn't — had three children by a giantess named Angrboda, and the three children were each, in their separate ways, the end of something. The first was Hel, half rose-faced and half corpse-blue, who would rule the dead. The second was Jörmungandr, the world-serpent, who would grow long enough to bite his own tail at the bottom of the sea. The third was a wolf, and his name was Fenrir.",
        "When the gods learned what Loki had been raising in secret, they went and took the three of them. Hel they sent down. The serpent they hurled into the sea. The wolf they brought back to Asgard, because the wolf was small and bright-eyed and seemed at first like a creature one could perhaps raise differently.",
        "He grew. He grew faster than the gods had been ready for. By the end of the first season he was the size of a horse. By the end of the second he was bigger than any horse anyone had ever seen. He ate enormous helpings. He looked at you when you came into his pen with a slow, intelligent, almost amused look, and the look made even the gods, who were not afraid of much, slightly uncomfortable.",
        "Tyr was the only one who fed him. Tyr was the god of the spear, the god of the just deal, the god who would later give the day called Tuesday his name. Tyr was not afraid of the wolf. Tyr did not like the wolf, exactly, but he respected him, and he believed in feeding the things that lived in your house, and so he brought the meat himself, every day, and the wolf would lift his head when Tyr came in and lower it again when the meal was set down, and that was their particular contract.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Odin had seen the future. He had paid for it at Mimir's well. He had seen what this wolf would do — would, eventually, swallow him whole at the day called Ragnarok, the end of the gods. He could not kill the wolf in cold blood; the laws of his own house forbade it, and besides, the future could not be cheated by killing the thing that was supposed to do the killing. The thing would happen another way. So he settled for binding.",
        "The first chain was named Læding, and the gods made a great show of asking Fenrir to test his strength against it. \"For sport,\" they said, casually, leaning. The wolf, who was vain, agreed, and let them wrap him, and on the first easy stretch of his shoulders the chain shattered like an old branch. The gods clapped politely and said wasn't that wonderful.",
        "The second chain was Drómi, twice the weight of the first. Again the wolf agreed. Again he stretched. Again the chain broke, in pieces this time, with a sound like the falling of bells. The gods clapped again and the clapping was a little nervous now.",
        "Odin sent down to the dwarves under the mountain. Make me, he said, a binding that the wolf cannot break. Use anything. Use materials I have not heard of. Use the impossible.",
        "The dwarves laughed. \"We can do it,\" they said. \"It will take us a long time, and we will need strange things. We will need the sound of a cat's footstep. We will need the beard of a woman. We will need the roots of a mountain and the breath of a fish and the spittle of a bird and the sinews of a bear.\" They sent out for those things. They brought them back. They wove them into a single ribbon, slender as a silk cord, soft to the hand. They called it Gleipnir. They handed it up.",
        "It looked like nothing. It looked like a gift you might give a child.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The gods went down to the wolf with the silken cord. \"For sport,\" they said again, but they were not as smooth this time, and the wolf had grown old enough now to read faces.",
        "He looked at the cord. He looked at the gods. He looked back at the cord. \"That,\" he said carefully, \"is too thin. There is something in it I don't like. I think you have made it not to be broken.\"",
        "The gods murmured. They argued. They said it would be no test of strength to break a thing that looked so weak. They said it was beneath him to refuse. They said all the things you say to flatter a creature into a trap.",
        "Fenrir let them talk. Then he said, \"All right. I'll let you bind me with it. But — \" his eyes went around the half-circle of gods \" — one of you must put his hand in my mouth. As surety. As proof you are not playing me false. If I break the cord, no one is hurt. If I cannot break it and you do not free me, the hand is mine.\"",
        "There was a silence. The gods looked at each other. Each god, in turn, found a reason to look at the floor.",
        "Tyr stepped forward. He did it without speaking. He laid his right hand into the wolf's mouth, palm flat, fingers spread. The wolf closed his teeth gently around the wrist. The wolf and the god looked at each other, and they understood each other completely, in that terrible quiet way that two honest beings sometimes do.",
        "The gods bound him. The cord went around his shoulders, his haunches, his throat. They tightened it. The wolf surged. The wolf strained. The cord did not give. The cord did not even creak. The wolf understood, in the moment of straining, that he had been deceived after all.",
        "The wolf's mouth closed.",
        "Tyr stepped back, holding the stump where his right hand had been, white-faced, but he did not cry out. He had given his oath. He had paid for it at the rate they had agreed.",
        { style: "quote", text: "There are bargains a god makes which save the world for a season and cost him a part of himself forever. Tyr's right hand is the price of every quiet century the gods have had since." },
        "They drove a sword sideways into the wolf's lower jaw, propped his mouth open, and left him bound on a lonely island in the cold sea, and the sound that came out of him went into the wind, and the wind has never quite stopped carrying it. He waits there still. The cord holds. It holds. It will hold until the day the world ends, and then it will not hold any longer, and Fenrir will rise, and the contract Tyr signed with his hand will run out at last."
    ]
},

{
    id: "thor-utgarda",
    title: "Thor in the Hall of Útgarða-Loki",
    subtitle: "What the great god lifted, and what the giants laughed at",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["Strength", "Illusion", "Humility", "Giants"],
    content: [
        "Thor was the strongest of the gods, and Thor knew it, and his arms knew it, and his hammer Mjölnir, which only he could lift, knew it, and the goats that pulled his chariot knew it. He did not wear his strength like a cloak. He wore it like skin. So when his cousin and traveling companion Loki suggested they go journeying east, into the country of the giants, just to see the hall of a giant-king named Útgarða-Loki, Thor said yes the way he said yes to most things — with the simplicity of a man who had not had cause to be wary of much.",
        "They took the chariot. They took the boy Þjálfi and his sister Röskva, who were quick-footed mortals Thor had picked up on a previous farm. They went east. The road was long. The trees thinned. The land became blue with cold.",
        "On the first night they camped in a hall they took to be empty — no light, no fire, just a great wide structure standing alone in a clearing — and slept badly, because the hall shook all night with what they took to be a storm. In the morning they discovered they had slept in the thumb-glove of a sleeping giant. The giant rose up to his full height and the sky darkened by half. He laughed mildly at them. He said his name was Skrýmir. He offered to walk with them a day.",
        "Skrýmir was so large that the path he took did not feel like a path; it felt like watching a cliff-face move next to you. That night Thor — irritated by the giant's snoring, which knocked acorns off the trees in three counties — crept up while Skrýmir slept and struck the giant's forehead with Mjölnir. He struck with all his strength. Skrýmir opened one eye sleepily and said, \"A leaf has fallen on me, I think,\" and rolled over.",
        "Thor struck again, harder, in the middle of the night. Skrýmir said, \"An acorn,\" and snored on.",
        "Thor struck a third time at dawn, with a blow that should have split a small mountain, and Skrýmir sat up and yawned and said, \"Some birds are restless this morning. Are you well?\"",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Thor was not well. They came on the next day to the hall of Útgarða-Loki, and the hall was so big that Thor did not at first realize they had come to it; he kept walking, expecting it to come closer. Útgarða-Loki was sitting on a throne the size of a barn, and he leaned down, and he laughed at them with the same mild laugh Skrýmir had used.",
        "\"Welcome, little gods,\" he said. \"Tell me, what is each of you good at? My court is dull tonight. Entertain me.\"",
        "Loki said, \"I can eat anything quicker than any creature alive.\" Útgarða-Loki summoned a man named Logi, and they were both set before a long trough of meat, and they ate. They met in the middle. But Logi had eaten the trough also, and the bones, and Loki had only eaten the meat, and Loki had lost.",
        "Þjálfi said, \"I can run faster than any creature alive.\" Útgarða-Loki summoned a small thin lad named Hugi, and they raced, and Hugi was at the finish line before the boy had reached the halfway mark. Three times. Three losses.",
        "Then it was Thor's turn. He stood up. He cracked his knuckles. He said, with the modesty of someone who has already decided which contests he is most likely to win, \"I'll drink. I'll drink anything you put in front of me.\"",
        "Útgarða-Loki signaled. A horn was brought — long, ribbed, ordinary-looking. \"Three pulls,\" said the giant-king, \"and any man at this court can drain it in one. My littlest man can drain it in two. Try.\"",
        "Thor put the horn to his lips. He drank long. He drank with the heaviness of a god. He paused for breath. The level in the horn had not noticeably moved. He drank again, longer this time, until his eyes watered. He set it down. The level might have dropped a fingerbreadth. He drank a third time, with his whole chest. The horn was as full as before, almost.",
        "He set it down. He was breathing hard. He had failed.",
        "\"Cat,\" suggested Útgarða-Loki kindly. \"Lift my cat. Surely you can lift a small grey cat off a hearth?\"",
        "A cat was brought in. It looked, at first, like a normal hearth-cat, sitting and grooming a paw. Thor put his hands under its belly. He lifted. The cat became, somehow, the heaviest cat in the world. He strained. He grunted. With every ounce of him he managed at last to raise one paw. One single paw. The cat looked at him without much interest.",
        "\"Old woman,\" said Útgarða-Loki. \"Wrestle my old nurse. Just for sport.\"",
        "An old hag was led in, bent and toothless. Thor took her in a wrestler's grip. He pushed. He pulled. He twisted. The old woman did not move. She put one foot behind his ankle and slowly, calmly, brought him to one knee. The hall howled with laughter. Thor's face was the color of beets.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "The next morning Útgarða-Loki walked them politely to the gate of his hall. They stood at the threshold. He smiled.",
        "\"You should know,\" he said, \"that I am Skrýmir. The blows you struck me at night fell, not on my forehead, but on a mountainside I had set in their place. The mountain is now scarred — three deep valleys — and they will be there forever, and travellers will say \"those are the valleys Thor cut.\" The trough Loki ate from was matched against Wildfire, who eats trough, bone, and stone. The boy raced against Thought, who is in the finish line before he is at the start. The horn you drank from was set in the sea, and the level you brought it down to has made the world's first tide. The cat you lifted was Jörmungandr, the world-serpent who circles the earth, and you lifted his shoulder out of the ocean, and the gods of every country were terrified for an hour. The old woman was Old Age, and she has never been thrown by anyone, and she put you on one knee, which is more than I have ever seen done to her.\"",
        "He inclined his head. \"You are stronger,\" he said, \"than we knew. Stronger than is comfortable. We will not invite you again.\"",
        "Then the hall behind them was not there. The land where the hall had been was empty hill country. Thor turned in fury and lifted his hammer to strike — and the giant was gone, too.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Even the strongest god can be made small by clever measurement. The lesson is not that the strength was a lie. The lesson is that the world is larger than the rooms in which strength is usually tested." },
        "He went home thoughtful. He was, perhaps, a little kinder to the goats after that. He did not mention the visit to the other gods for a long time."
    ]
},

{
    id: "ragnarok",
    title: "Ragnarok",
    subtitle: "The twilight of the gods, foreseen and walked into anyway",
    civilization: "norse",
    themes: ["End of the world", "Doom", "Inevitability", "Rebirth"],
    content: [
        "The gods of the North did not believe their world was permanent. The gods of the North believed their world would end, and would end badly, and would end at a date that was already inked into the calendar. Odin had paid in an eye to know this. He had been told by the seer beside the well exactly how it would happen. He had not been told how to stop it. He had been told only that he would not stop it, and that the trying would itself be a form of the not stopping.",
        "There would come first a winter. Not a winter — three winters, one after the other, with no summer between them. The cattle would die. The crops would not come up. Brothers would kill brothers for a heel of bread. The morality of the upper world would crack and fall like ice in the spring, except there would be no spring. This was called the Fimbulvetr. It was the warning.",
        "Then the wolf Fenrir, bound on his island, would slip his cord at last. The chain Gleipnir, made by the dwarves of impossible things, would frail at one strand and then another, and the wolf would stand up to his full height — which by now was the height of a small mountain — and walk into the world with his mouth so wide that his upper jaw scraped the sky and his lower jaw dragged in the sea.",
        "Jörmungandr, the world-serpent, would come up out of the deep at the same hour. The waters would rise. Coastal cities would be carried away in the long surge.",
        "The boat Naglfar — built, all the long centuries, of the untrimmed nails of dead men — would slip its mooring and sail across the flooded plains, and on its deck would stand the army of the giants and the dishonored dead, with Loki at the helm.",
        "Surt — the fire-giant of the south — would ride up out of his country with a sword that burned brighter than the sun, and where the sword passed, the world would burn after it.",
        "And the gods, who had known all of this for a very long time, would put on their armor and go out to meet it.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "Odin met Fenrir. He had known he would. He had raised the wolf as best as could be done. He went out anyway, in his blue cloak, with Gungnir his spear, and the wolf opened the mouth that had been growing for it, and the All-Father went down into that mouth, and was gone, and the lighting of his life — the long, shrewd, one-eyed lighting — went out at last.",
        "His son Víðarr, who almost no one had paid much attention to in the long peaceful centuries, ran forward. He had a particular boot. The boot had been made, scrap by scrap, from every leather offcut that any cobbler in any country had ever discarded — because Víðarr was the god of the careful keeping of small things, and the offcuts had been adding up. With that boot he stepped onto the lower jaw of Fenrir and pinned it. With his hands he gripped the upper jaw. He pulled. The wolf's mouth was rent in two. The wolf fell. Víðarr stood among the carcass and did not weep, because there was no time.",
        "Thor met Jörmungandr. He had known he would. The two of them had been waiting for each other since the day Thor had lifted the cat in Útgarða-Loki's hall. Thor swung Mjölnir. The hammer struck the great head of the serpent. The skull cracked. The serpent fell. Thor stood in the slack coils of the dead snake and breathed, satisfied. Then he tried to walk. Then he found he could not.",
        "Nine steps. He took nine steps. The serpent's last breath had carried venom that even a god could not metabolize. On the ninth step his knees gave way. He went down beside what he had killed, and the strongest of the gods died beside the longest of the snakes, and they made a tangle of stillness on the gray earth.",
        "Tyr, who was missing his right hand, met the dog Garmr at the gate of the underworld, and they killed each other. Heimdall, who was the watcher of the rainbow bridge, met Loki, and they killed each other. Surt's sword met Freyr, the lord of grain, who had given up his own sword for love long ago, and Freyr went down with nothing in his hand, and the wheat of the world fell with him.",
        "The bridge cracked. The hall Valhalla burned. The trees of Yggdrasil shook so badly that even the eagle at the top fell out of his place and dropped through the smoke. Surt, at last, drew his sword across the whole sky, and the sky caught, and the fire took everything — gods, giants, men, beasts, halls, ships, mountains — and the sea rose to meet it, and where sea and fire met there was only steam, and after the steam there was nothing.",
        { style: "hr" },
        "And then, after a long time during which the world was nothing, a green shoot.",
        "A green shoot, in mud, in a quiet morning. The sea had retreated. The sky had cleared. The earth had risen back up, washed, and a sun — a new one, the daughter of the old sun, born just before the old sun was eaten — climbed slowly into a fresh day.",
        "And out of a hollow in the trunk of a single surviving ash, Líf and Lífþrasir came stepping. They were a man and a woman. They had hidden in the tree. They had eaten the morning dew. They had not died. They walked out into the new world, and they were the beginning of everything again.",
        "And among the new grass — for the new grass was already springing — the gods who had survived (for some had survived; Víðarr had survived, the sons of Thor had survived, Baldr had been let up out of Hel because there was no Hel anymore) sat down in a circle and began to talk quietly about how to do it differently this time.",
        { style: "quote", text: "Doom in the country of the North is not a wall. Doom is a hinge. The world ends and then the world begins, and the gods walk into the ending knowing this — which is, perhaps, why they walked." },
        "They found, among the grass, the gold pieces of a chess set the old gods had used. The pieces had survived. Someone — nobody remembered who — picked them up and set them out, and a game began that is still being played, and the wind that blew across the new grass that morning was very nearly clean."
    ]
}
);

/* ────────── Sort stories by canonical civilization order ────────── */
(function () {
    const order = window.MYTHOLOGY.civilizations.map(c => c.id);
    const indexOf = id => {
        const i = order.indexOf(id);
        return i < 0 ? 999 : i;
    };
    window.MYTHOLOGY.stories.sort((a, b) => {
        const da = indexOf(a.civilization);
        const db = indexOf(b.civilization);
        if (da !== db) return da - db;
        return 0;
    });
})();

